But whatever hopes Ι had formed that the book would give more assistance than has been hitherto easily accessible to the general student of this portion of Tacitus have been far more than realized by the reception given to it, and by the demand for a new edition at an earlier date than l had expected. The defects still evident in it will not, l hope, be set down to negligente, but will be excused as those of an editor who has long since lost the experience which those engaged in teaching acquire of what is most likely to interest or perplex intelligent students.
